$ Bash built-in read: read one line from stdin and assign words to variables
@ read

By default, `read` reads a line from → development/stdin-stdout-stderr[stdin] and assigns the read words to → Linux/shell/bash/variables[variables].

{ Reading from stdin

  Reading from stdin and assigning to → Linux/shell/bash/variables[variables].
  
  gh|about-Bash|/built-in/read/stdin||

}
{ echo'ing into read vs using a here string #bash-read-here-string

  With a → Linux/shell/bash/redirection#bash-here-string[here string], it's possible to assign values to variables *and* retain the values because no new subshell is started:

  gh|about-Bash|/built-in/read/echo-vs-here-string||

